{"title_page": "Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame", "text_new": "{{primary sources|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame\n| image = <!-- optional -->\n| caption = <!-- optional -->\n| established = May 2002\n| dissolved = <!-- optional -->\n| location = 2701 Grant Avenue, [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania 19114\n| type = Nonprofit Corporation\n| visitors = <!-- optional -->\n| director = <!-- optional -->\n| leader_title = President\n| leader_name = Ken Avallon\n| website = {{URL|http://www.phillyhall.org}}\n}}\n'''The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame''' is a nonprofit organization in [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, U.S., that was established in May 2002, to honor individuals and groups who are either area natives who became prominent in the field of sports or who became prominent in the field of sports in the region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/mission.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/history.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Hall of Fame's address is 2701 Grant Avenue Philadelphia, PA 19114.  Phone number:  215.254.5049\n\nFrom 2004 to 2010, the organization also presented an annual \"Pride of Philadelphia Award\" to a team or individual.<ref name=PrideOfPhiladelphia/>\n\n==Requirements==\nIndividuals, Teams, Venues, Events, and Organizations are all eligible.  Generally they must have gained national prominence as individuals or venues while attached to the Philadelphia region, or won a championship as a team from the Philadelphia region.  Individuals are eligible for induction five years after retirement from a playing career.  When an individual dies, he or she becomes immediately eligible.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillyhall.org/nomination.html |title=NOMINATION & ELECTION |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame |accessdate=December 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn individual who was not an athlete may be inducted in the following categories: Legacy of Excellence, Lifetime Commitment, Philadelphia Medal.\n\n== Inductees ==\n[[File:Richie Ashburn 1953.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Richie Ashburn]], inducted in 2004, longtime player and radio broadcaster for the Philadelphia Phillies.]]\n[[File:Wilt Chamberlain3.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Wilt Chamberlain]], an inaugural class inductee, was born and raised in Philadelphia and played for the Warriors and 76ers.]]\n[[File:Jimmie Foxx 1937 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Jimmie Foxx]], inducted in 2004, played for the Philadelphia Athletics.]]\n[[File:Connie Mack3.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Connie Mack]], longtime Manager and Owner of the Philadelphia Athletics was inducted in 2004.]]\n[[File:Bill Tilden.jpg|thumb|200px|Tennis champion [[Bill Tilden]], inducted in 2004, was born and raised in the Philadelphia area.]]\n[[File:Phillies-Parade Harry-K crop.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Harry Kalas]], longtime Phillies broadcaster, was the 2004 Legacy of Excellence inductee.]]\n[[File:Barkley Lipofsky.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Charles Barkley]], inducted in 2005, played for the Philadelphia 76ers from 1984\u20131992.]]\n[[File:Reggie.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Reggie Jackson]], a 2006 inductee, was born and raised in the Philadelphia area.]]\n[[File:Merrill Reese at Lehigh U. 080805-F-9429S-003 crop.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Merrill Reese]], inducted in 2009, long time radio broadcaster for the Philadelphia Eagles.]]\n[[File:Mark Howe.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Mark Howe]], inducted in 2011, played for the Philadelphia Flyers.]]\n[[File:Joe McCarthy.png|thumb|right|180px|[[Joe McCarthy (manager)|Joe McCarthy]], inducted in 2011, born and raised in the Philadelphia area.]]\n[[File:Moses Malone.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Moses Malone]], played for the 76ers.]]\n[[File:TommyLasorda.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Tommy Lasorda]], born and raised in Philadelphia area.]]\n[[File:Marvin Harrison in 2007 Training Camp 2.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Marvin Harrison]], born and raised in Philadelphia area.]]\n\n=== Key ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background: #E9E9E9;\" | Inducted\n| The year the person was inducted into the Hall.\n|-\n|style=\"background: #E9E9E9;\" | Person\n| The person's name.\n|-\n|style=\"background: #E9E9E9;\" | Sport\n| The sport the person was inducted in.\n|-\n|style=\"background: #E9E9E9;\" | Organization\n| The organization(s) that connect the person to the Philadelphia area.\n|-\n| Reference\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phillyhall.org/inductees.asp |title=INDUCTEES |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame |accessdate=December 26, 2009}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! '''Inducted'''\n! '''Person'''\n! '''Sport'''\n! '''Organization'''\n|-\n|rowspan=21|2004\n| [[Paul Arizin]]\n| Basketball\n| Local, [[La Salle College High School]], [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova University]], [[Golden State Warriors#1946\u20131962: Two championships in Philadelphia|Philadelphia Warriors]]\n|- style=\"background:#ffe6bd;\"\n||[[Richie Ashburn]]\n||Baseball\n||[[Philadelphia Phillies]]\n|-\n| [[Chuck Bednarik]]\n| [[American football|Football]]\n| [[Penn Quakers football|University of Pennsylvania]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n|- style=\"background:#ffe6bd;\"\n||[[Bert Bell]]\n||Football\n||Local, University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia Eagles\n|-\n| [[Steve Carlton]]\n| Baseball\n| Philadelphia Phillies\n|- style=\"background:#ffe6bd;\"\n||[[Wilt Chamberlain]]\n||Basketball\n||Local, [[Overbrook High School (Philadelphia)|Overbrook High]], Philadelphia Warriors, [[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|-\n| [[Bobby Clarke]]\n| [[Ice hockey|Hockey]]\n| [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n|- style=\"background:#ffe6bd;\"\n||[[Billy Cunningham]]\n||Basketball\n||Philadelphia 76ers\n|-\n| [[Julius Erving]]\n| Basketball\n| Philadelphia 76ers\n|- style=\