de of Philadelphia Award==\n[[File:Smarty jones.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Smarty Jones]], a 2004 awardee.]]\n[[File:Ryan Howard3.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ryan Howard]], a 2006 awardee.]]\n[[File:Philadelphia Phillies Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|upright|The 2008 Phillies with President [[Barack Obama]] at the [[White House]].]]\n\nThe '''Pride of Philadelphia''' Award is given to teams or individuals who have \"represented the Philadelphia area with dignity, determination, and class through athletic achievement.\"<ref name=PrideOfPhiladelphia>{{cite web |title=PRIDE OF PHILADELPHIA |publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/prideofphila.asp |accessdate=August 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\n;2004\n*[[Smarty Jones]], winner, [[Kentucky Derby]] / Preakness Stakes\n*[[Bernard Hopkins]], [[Undisputed middleweight champion]]\n*[[2003\u201304 Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball team|St. Joseph's Men's Basketball]], [[Atlantic 10 Men's Basketball Tournament|Atlantic 10 East Division Champions]]\n\n;2005\n*[[Afleet Alex]], winner, [[Preakness Stakes]] / [[Belmont Stakes]]\n*[[Philadelphia Phantoms]], [[List of Calder Cup champions|Calder Cup AHL Champions]]\n\n;2006\n*Prep Charter Boys' Basketball, PIAA Class AA Basketball Champions\n*[[2005\u201306 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova Men's Basketball]], [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East Regular Season Co-Champions]]\n*[[Ryan Howard]], [[NL MVP]]\n\n;2007\n*[[Jimmy Rollins]], NL MVP, [[Gold Glove]]\n*[[Cheltenham High School|Cheltenham High School Girls' Basketball]], PIAA AAAA State Champions\n\n;2008\n*[[2008 Philadelphia Phillies season|2008 Philadelphia Phillies]], [[2008 World Series|World Series Champions]]\n*[[Philadelphia Soul]], Arena Bowl XXII Champions\n*[[Mount Saint Joseph Academy (Flourtown, Pennsylvania)|Mount Saint Joseph Academy Girls Basketball]], 2008 PIAA AAA State Champions\n\n;2009\n*[[2008\u201309 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova Men's Basketball]], [[2009 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2009 NCAA Final Four]]\n*[[Archbishop John Carroll High School (Radnor, Pennsylvania)|Archbishop Carroll boys' and girls' basketball teams]], PIAA AAA State Champions\n*[[Miguel Cartagena]], 2009 [[Golden Gloves]] Champion\n\n;2010<ref>{{cite web|first=William|last=Zeltman|title=Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame 2010 Induction|date=November 13, 2010|publisher=Bleacher Report, Inc.|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/516880-philadelphia-sports-hall-of-fame-2010-induction|accessdate=2010-11-22}}</ref>\n*[[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]], Phillies\n*[[2009 Villanova Wildcats football team|Villanova football]], FCS National Champions\n*[[Mark Herzlich]], Boston College linebacker\n\n==Roll Call of Champions==\nThe hall of fame's website has a page that honors every Greater Philadelphia team\u2014college and professional\u2014that won the championship in its particular sport.<ref>'''''At''''' the following webpage, '''''click on the link''''' to a particular sport. {{cite web|title=Roll Call of Champions|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/champions.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Hall of Fame Charities==\nThe Foundation formed Hall of Fame Charities in 2004. It supports or has formed partnerships with organizations in the [[Greater Philadelphia]] area that promote youth sports, especially at the pre-teen, grade-school level. These organizations include: Richie Ashburn Baseball Foundation, Police Athletic League (PAL) Junior Golf, Arthur Ashe Youth Tennis and Education, Bruce Simon Southampton Summer Basketball Camp, The First Tee of Philadelphia, and [[Ed Snider Youth Hockey Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Youth Sports|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/youth.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref>\n\nHall of Fame Charities also has student<ref>{{cite web|title=Student Programs|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/student.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref> and community<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Programs|publisher=The Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame Foundation|url=http://www.phillyhall.org/community.html|accessdate=2011-11-04}}</ref> programs.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia}}\n\n*[[Sports in Philadelphia]]\n*{{ section link|Philadelphia Eagles|Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame}}\n*{{slink|List of Philadelphia Flyers award winners|Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame}}\n*{{slink|List of Philadelphia Phillies award winners and league leaders|Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame}}\n*{{slink|Philadelphia 76ers|Philadelphia Sports Hall of Fame}}\n*[[Philadelphia Sports Writers Association]]\n*[[Pennsylvania Sports Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.phillyhall.org}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Philadelphia Phillies}}\n{{Philadelphia Eagles}}\n{{Philadelphia Flyers}}\n{{Philadelphia 76ers}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Sports in Philadelphia|*]]\n[[Category:Culture of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:All-sports halls of fame]]\n[[Category:Halls of fame in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sports museums in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sports in Pennsylvania|>]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2002]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "CHIP72", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInductees", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Sports_Hall_of_Fame"}
{"title_page": "Red August", "text_new": "[[File:MaoZedong19660818.jpg|alt=|thumb|283x283px|On August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Red Guards]] on [[Tiananmen]] for the first time, triggering massive slaughter in Beijing. ]]\nThe '''Red August''' ({{zh|s=\u7ea2\u516b\u6708 |t=\u7d05\u516b\u6708 |p=H\u00f3ng B\u0101yu\u00e8}}), originally meaning the August of 1966 of the [[Cultural Revolution]], is also used to indicate a series of [[massacre]]s in [[Beijing]] which mainly took place during the period.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/docs/2001_03_05.pdf|title=Student Attacks Against Teachers: The Revolution of 1966|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=2001|website=University of Chicago|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k9NQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=Daxing+Massacre#v=onepage|title=Historical Dictionary of the Chinese Cultural Revolution|last=Jian|first=Guo|last2=Song|first2=Yongyi|last3=Zhou|first3=Yuan|date=2015-07-23|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-5172-4|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|date=2014-12-07|title=A Massacre in Daxing County During the Cultural Revolution|journal=Chinese Law & Government|volume=14|issue=3|pages=70\u201371|language=en|doi=10.2753/CLG0009-4609140370}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/09/13/china-communist-party-grandfather-survived-cultural-revolution-why-does-he-still-love-mao/|title=My Grandfather Survived China's Cultural Revolution. Why Does He Still Love Mao?|last=Dong|first=Yifu|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Jian|first=Guo|url=https://books.google.com/?id=T5-4zOdHKOIC&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA237&dq=Historical+Dictionary+of+the+Chinese+Cultural+Revolution+red+august|title=Historical Dictionary of the Chinese Cultural Revolution|last2=Song|first2=Yongyi|last3=Zhou|first3=Yuan|date=2006-07-17|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6491-7|language=en}}</ref> According to the official statistics in 1980, from August to September in 1966, a total of 1,772 people\u2014including teachers and principals of many schools\u2014were killed in Beijing by [[Red Guards]]; in addition, 33,695 homes were ransacked and 85,196 families were forced to leave the city.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifengweekly.com/detil.php?id=604 |script-title=zh:\u600e\u6837\u53cd\u601d\u201c\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u201d|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u5468\u520a|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2011/09/201109160825.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u201c\u975e\u6b63\u5e38\u6b7b\u4ea1\u201d\u4e86\u591a\u5c11\u4eba\uff1f ---- \u8bfb\u82cf\u626c\u7684\u300a\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u4e2d\u56fd\u519c\u6751\u7684\u96c6\u4f53\u5c60\u6740\u300b|last=Song|first=Yongyi|date=|publisher=\u535a\u8baf|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2014/01/23/265228870/chinese-red-guards-apologize-reopening-a-dark-chapter|title=Chinese Red Guards Apologize, Reopening A Dark Chapter|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The killing by the Red Guards also made an impact on several rural districts of Beijing, causing the \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\", for example, during which 325 people were killed from August 27 to September 1 in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1994/07/18/a-nightmare-leaves-scars-questions/05791e4e-e4a4-49b8-b235-c440f51783c0/|title=A NIGHTMARE LEAVES SCARS, QUESTIONS|last=Southerl|first=Daniel|date=1994-07-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The oldest killed during the Daxing Massacre was 80 years old, while the youngest was only 38 days old; 22 families were wiped out.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://mjlsh.usc.cuhk.edu.hk/Book.aspx?cid=4&tid=2464 |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u65f6\u671f\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5174\u53bf\u5927\u5c60\u6740\u8c03\u67e5|last=Yu|first=Luowen|date=|publisher=Chinese University of Hong Kong|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Scholars have also pointed out that, according to the official statistics in 1985, the actual death toll during the Red August was over 10,000.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://beijingspring.com/bj2/2010/170/201332200545.htm |script-title=zh:\u8bb0\u4e0b\u8001\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u7684\u8840\u503a|last=Peng|first=Xiaoming|date=|publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u4e4b\u6625|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.boxun.com/hero/201203/beijingzhoumoshihui/18_1.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5927\u7b11\u8c08\u6740\u4eba/\u585e\u9e3f\u79cb /\u5317\u4eac\u5468\u672b\u8bd7\u4f1a|author=|first=|date=|publisher=Boxun|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Song Binbin]], a leader of the Red Guards, on [[Tiananmen|Tiananmen of Beijing]], which greatly encouraged the Red Guards who then started their massive killing in the city.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Methods of slaughter during the Red August included beating, whipping, strangling, trampling, boiling, beheading and so on; in particular, the method used to kill most infants and children were knocking them against the ground or slicing them in halves.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/victim_ebook_070505.pdf |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u53d7\u96be\u8005 \u2014\u2014\u5173\u4e8e\u8feb\u5bb3\u3001\u76d1\u7981\u548c\u6740\u622e\u7684\u5bfb\u8bbf\u5b9e\u5f55|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=|publisher=[[University of Chicago]] |language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2013/08/201308012335.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5174\u6587\u9769\u5c60\u6740\uff1a\u5a74\u513f\u88ab\u5288\u6210\u4e24\u534a|author=|first=|date=|publisher=Boxun|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipkmedia.com/%e9%9b%86%e4%bd%93%e9%81%97%e5%bf%98%e6%96%87%e9%9d%a9%ef%bc%8c%e6%97%a0%e7%96%91%e6%98%af%e4%b8%80%e7%a7%8d%e6%9b%b4%e6%b7%b1%e8%bf%9c%e7%9a%84%e6%b0%91%e6%97%8f%e5%85%ac%e8%80%bb/ |script-title=zh:\u96c6\u4f53\u9057\u5fd8\u6587\u9769\uff0c\u65e0\u7591\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u66f4\u6df1\u8fdc\u7684\u6c11\u65cf\u516c\u803b|last=|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u5149\u4f20\u5a92|language=zh|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Many people, including the notable writer [[Lao She]], committed suicide after being persecuted.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/rct/pdf/e_outputs/b10/v10p005.pdf|title=Death and the Nobel-On Lao She's \"Suicide\"|last=Brady|first=Paul|date=1974|website=Chinese University of Hong Kong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> During the massacres, Mao Zedong publicly opposed any government intervention to the student movement, and [[Xie Fuzhi]], the Minister of [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], also ordered to protect the Red Guards and not arrest them.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=%E5%8C%97%E4%BA%AC+%E5%A6%82%E6%9E%9C%E4%BD%A0%E6%8A%8A%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA%E7%9A%84%E4%BA%BA%E6%89%A3%E7%95%99%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E6%8D%95%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E4%BD%A0%E4%BB%AC%E5%B0%B1%E8%A6%81%E7%8A%AF%E9%94%99%E8%AF%AF#v=onepage |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":33\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/history/zhiqing/ziliao/detail_2012_09/01/17271511_0.shtml?_from_ralated |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u516c\u5b89\u90e8\u957f\u8c22\u5bcc\u6cbb\u8c08\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u6253\u6b7b\u4eba\uff1a\u6211\u4eec\u7ba1\u4e0d\u7740|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/shendu/nfzm/detail_2014_03/14/34768339_0.shtml |script-title=zh:\u535e\u4ef2\u8018\u4e08\u592b\uff1a\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u6ca1\u53c2\u4e0e\u6253\u4eba \u4f46\u5979\u662f\u4e00\u4f19\u513f\u7684|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/history/zhiqing/ziliao/200912/1214_6858_1473893.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5bf9\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u7ec4\u7ec7\u5931\u53bb\u4fe1\u4efb \u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u51b3\u5b9a\u4e0b\u653e\u77e5\u9752\u59cb\u672b|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> However, things had grown out of control by the end of August 1966, forcing the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] (CPC) and Chinese government to take multiple interventions, which gradually brought the massacre to an end.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnd.org/CR/ZK06/cr340.gb.html |script-title=zh:\u300a\u4eb2\u5386\u91cd\u5e86\u5927\u6b66\u6597\u300b\u5e8f|author=\u738b\u5e74\u4e00|date=|publisher=\u534e\u590f\u6587\u6458|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nThe Red August of Beijing is regarded as the origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the Chinese Cultural Revolution, influencing the Red Guards' movement in multiple cities including [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Nanjing]] and [[Xiamen]], where local political leaders, intellectuals, teachers and people of [[Five Black Categories]] were persecuted and killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR43&lpg=PR43&dq=%E7%BA%A2%E8%89%B2%E6%81%90%E6%80%96#v=onepage |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/mandarin/zhuanlan/xinlingzhilyu/wengebeiwanglu/m0816mind-08152013163142.html |script-title=zh:47\u5468\u5e74\u56de\u653e\uff1a\u518d\u5fc6\u6587\u9769\u201c\u516b.\u4e00\u516b\u201d\u548c \u201c\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\u201d|work=Radio Free Asia|language=zh-cn|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinesepen.org/blog/archives/61964 |script-title=zh:\u91d1\u949f\uff1a\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\uff0c\u8840\u8ff9\u672a\u4e7e|author=|date=|publisher=\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u6587\u7b14\u4f1a|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/rain/a/20130928003840 |script-title=zh:1966\u5e74\u9996\u90fd\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u4e0a\u6d77\u641e\u6b66\u6597:\u6ca1\u6253\u6b7b\u5c31\u662f\u6587\u6597|author=|date=|publisher=[[Tencent]] |accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/bianzhongyun_text2.htm |script-title=zh:\u535e\u4ef2\u8018\u7eaa\u5ff5\u6587\u7ae0\uff08\u7eed\uff09|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=|publisher=University of Chicago|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> There has been comparison between the 18 August 1966, which was the key point of the Red August, and the ''[[Kristallnacht]],'' which was the prelude of [[Nazi Germany]]'s [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/zh/%E7%8E%8B%E5%AE%B9%E8%8A%AC%E7%BB%8F%E5%8E%86%E7%9A%84818/a-15326044 |script-title=zh:\u738b\u5bb9\u82ac\u7ecf\u5386\u7684\"8\u00b718\"|last=|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u5fb7\u56fd\u4e4b\u58f0|language=zh|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mjlsh.org/book.aspx?cid=2&tid=2835&pid=7350 |script-title=zh:\u6c89\u91cd\u7684\u56de\u5fc6\uff0841\uff09\u201c\u6587\u9769\u201d\u98ce\u66b4\u5230\u6765\u7684\u65f6\u5019|author=|date=|publisher=[[Chinese University of Hong Kong]] |accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2012/04/201204232254.shtml |script-title=zh:\u7280\u5229\u516c\uff1a\u4e5f\u8bf4\u201c\u8001\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u201d|author=|date=|publisher=\u535a\u8baf|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnd.org/CR/ZK12/cr696.gb.html |script-title=zh:\u4f2b\u89c6\u738b\u6676\u579a\uff0d\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u5bf9\u7c3f\u5386\u53f2\u7684\u516c\u5802\u2014\u2014\u300a\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u8c08\u8bdd\u7eaa\u8981\u300b\u7684\u89e3\u8bfb\u53ca\u5176\u5b83\uff08\u4e0b\uff09|author=\u90ce\u94a7|date=|publisher=\u534e\u590f\u6587\u6458|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite journal|last=Ma|first=Sheng-Mei|title=Contrasting Two Survival Literatures: On the Jewish Holocaust and the Chinese Cultural Revolution|date=1987-01-01|url=https://academic.oup.com/hgs/article/2/1/81/759930|journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=81\u201393|doi=10.1093/hgs/2.1.81|issn=8756-6583}}</ref> The Red August along with the following massacres across China during the Cultural Revolution has also been compared to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] made by the [[Armed Forces of the Empire of Japan|Japanese military]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20181213-notes-nanjing-massacre/ |script-title=zh:\u8b80\u8005\u4f86\u51fd\uff1a\u5efa\u69cb\u6587\u5316\u5275\u50b7\u2014\u2014\u5f9e\u5357\u4eac\u5927\u5c60\u6bba\u8207\u300c\u6587\u9769\u300d\u8aaa\u8d77|author=\u843d\u65e5\u9918\u71c8|date=|publisher=\u7aef\u50b3\u5a92\u79d1\u6280|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://listsprd.osu.edu/pipermail/mclc/2016-May/005028.html|title=MCLC: Ma JIan on the CR anniversary|last=LIST|first=MCLC|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== History of the massacre ==\n\n=== Historical background ===\nOn May 16, 1966, Cultural Revolution began in [[Mainland China|mainland, China]]. On August 5th, [[Bian Zhongyun]], the first vice-principal of the [[Experimental High School Attached to Beijing Normal University]], was beaten to death by [[Red Guards]] and was first education worker in Beijing killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Massacre in Beijing ===\nOn August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Song Binbin]], a leader of the Red Guards, on [[Tiananmen|Tiananmen of Beijing]], where Mao asked Song if the \"Bin\" in her first name was the same character as the \"Bin\" in [[Chengyu|Chinese Chengyu]] \"Wen Zhi Bin Bin (\u6587\u8d28\u5f6c\u5f6c)\"; later, Mao commented on her name, \u201cYao Wu Ma (\u8981\u6b66\u561b)\u201d, meaning \"(you'd) better fight\". <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> After this meeting, the morale of the Red Guards was significantly boosted, which triggered their massive slaughter in Beijing.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In particular, on August 25, 1966, thousands of Red Guards started a week-long massacre in Ganlan Market (\u6984\u6746\u5e02) of the [[Chongwen District]] of Beijing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/317716627_99911659|title=\u6984\u6746\u5e02\u4e8b\u4ef6_\u5317\u4eac|website=www.sohu.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, 1966, Mao approved a document from the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], ordering \"do not use police force\u2014no exception\u2014to intervene or suppress the movement of revolutionary students\".<ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/mandarin/zhuanlan/xinlingzhilyu/wengebeiwanglu/m0816mind-08152013163142.html|title=47\u5468\u5e74\u56de\u653e\uff1a\u518d\u5fc6\u6587\u9769\"\u516b.\u4e00\u516b\"\u548c \"\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\"|website=Radio Free Asia|language=zh-cn|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite book|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=%E5%8C%97%E4%BA%AC+%E5%A6%82%E6%9E%9C%E4%BD%A0%E6%8A%8A%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA%E7%9A%84%E4%BA%BA%E6%89%A3%E7%95%99%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E6%8D%95%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E4%BD%A0%E4%BB%AC%E5%B0%B1%E8%A6%81%E7%8A%AF%E9%94%99%E8%AF%AF#v=onepage|title=\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|language=ru}}</ref> The next day, Mao gave a talk at the Work Conference of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Center]], publicly supporting students' movement and opposing any intervention to the Cultural Revolution of students:<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-9/mswv9_65.htm|title=Talk At The Work Conference Of The Centre|website=www.marxists.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/chinese/maozedong/1968/5-209.htm|author=|date=|publisher=\u4e2d\u6587\u9a6c\u514b\u601d\u4e3b\u4e49\u6587\u5e93|script-title=zh:\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5728\u4e2d\u592e\u5de5\u4f5c\u4f1a\u8bae\u4e0a\u7684\u8bb2\u8bdd\uff08\u4e00\u4e5d\u516d\u516d\u5e74\u516b\u6708\u4e8c\u5341\u4e09\u65e5\uff09|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><blockquote>In my view, Peking is not all that chaotic. The students held a meeting of 100,000 and then captured the murderers. This caused some panic. Peking is too gentle. Appeals have been issued, [but after all] there are very few hooligans. Stop interfering for the time being. It is still too early to say anything definite about the reorganization of the centre of the [Youth] League; let us wait four months. Decisions taken hurriedly can do only harm. Work teams were dispatched in a hurry; the left was struggled against in a hurry; meetings of 100,000 were called in a hurry; appeals were issued in a hurry; opposition to the new municipal [party] committee of Peking was said, in a hurry, to be tantamount to an opposition to the [party] Centre. Why is it impermissible to oppose K? I have issued a big character poster myself, \u2018Bombard the Headquarters!\u2019 Some problems have to be settled soon. For instance, the workers, peasants, and soldiers should not interfere with the students\u2019 great Cultural Revolution. Let the students go into the street. What is wrong with their writing big-character posters or going into the street? Let foreigners take pictures. They take shots to show aspects of our backward tendencies. But it does not matter. Let the imperialists make a scandal about us.</blockquote>On August 26, [[Xie Fuzhi]], the Minister of [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], also ordered to protect the Red Guards and not arrest them; he stated that it was not incorrect for the Red Guards to beat \"bad people\", and it was fine if the \"bad people\" were killed.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> The next day, the \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\" took place in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> Xie reiterated his points while meeting with the heads of several provincial public security systems, claiming that the killing by Red Guards was none of their business and it was a mistake if the public security was to arrest the Red Guards.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":31\" />\n\n=== The end of the massacre ===\nBy the end of August 1966, things had grown out of control, forcing the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] (CPC) and Chinese government to take multiple interventions, which gradually brought the massacre to an end.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> On September 5, ''[[People's Daily]]'' published an article (\"\u7528\u6587\u6597\uff0c\u4e0d\u7528\u6b66\u6597\"), calling for an end to the combat and massacre.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u8457|first=\u6768\u7ee7\u7ef3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT508&lpg=PT508&dq=%E7%94%A8%E6%96%87%E6%96%97%EF%BC%8C%E4%B8%8D%E7%94%A8%E6%AD%A6%E6%96%97+9%E6%9C%885%E6%97%A5#v=onepage|title=\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|language=zh}}</ref> \n\nNevertheless, millions of Red Guards continued to arrive in Beijing to see Mao Zedong at Tiananmen square on September 15 and October 1.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== The slaughter ==\n\n=== Methods of killing ===\nDuring the Red August, methods of slaughter used by Red Guards included beating, whipping, strangling, trampling, boiling, beheading and so on; in particular, the method used to kill most infants and children were knocking them against the ground or slicing them in halves.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n=== Death toll ===\n\n* According to the official statistics in 1980, from August to September in 1966, a total of 1,772 people\u2014including teachers and principals of many schools\u2014were killed in Beijing by [[Red Guards]]; in addition, 33,695 homes were ransacked and 85,196 families were forced to leave Beijing.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":20\" /> \n* In \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\", 325 people were killed from August 27 to September 1 in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n* Researchers have pointed out that, according to the official statistics in 1985, the actual death toll during the Red August was over 10,000; in addition, 92,000 homes were ransacked and 125,000 families were forced to leave the city.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":13\" />\n\n== Aftermath and influence ==\n[[File:Political_slogan_by_Red_Guards_on_the_campus_of_Fudan_University_1976.jpg|alt=|thumb|The Red Guards' political propaganda slogans on the wall of the campus of [[Shanghai Fudan University]]: \"Defend the Central Party Committee with blood and life! Defend Chairman Mao with blood and life! \u201d.]]\nThe Red August of Beijing is regarded as the origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the Chinese Cultural Revolution.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Some of the Red Guards from Beijing No.6 High School even wrote \"Long Live Red Terror!\" on the wall with the blood of their victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/wangguanghua.htm|title=\u5b66\u751f\u738b\u5149\u534e\u4e4b\u6b7b|author=Youqin, Wang|date=|work=The University of Chicago|publisher=|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226161900/http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/wangguanghua.htm|archive-date=2018-12-26|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Red August made an impact on the movement of Red Guards in multiple cities including [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Nanjing]] and [[Xiamen]], where local political leaders, intellectuals, teachers and people of [[Five Black Categories]] were persecuted and killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":28\" /><ref name=\":26\" /> For instance, on September 15, 1966, eleven Red Guards from [[Beijing Foreign Studies University]] united with Red Guards from [[Shanghai Foreign Language School]] in Shanghai, chanting \"Long Live Red Terror\" and subsequently persecuting 31 teachers.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nThere has been comparison between the 18 August 1966, which was the key point of the Red August, and the ''[[Kristallnacht]],'' which was the prelude of [[Nazi Germany]]'s [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":30\" /> The Red August along with the following massacres across China during the Cultural Revolution has also been compared to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] made by the [[Armed Forces of the Empire of Japan|Japanese military]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Red Terror]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n*[[Daxing Massacre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Political controversies in China]]\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights in China]]\n[[Category:1966 in Asia]]\n[[Category:1966 in China]]\n[[Category:1960s in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Beijing]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:MaoZedong19660818.jpg|alt=|thumb|283x283px|On August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Red Guards]] on [[Tiananmen]] for the first time, triggering massive slaughter in Beijing. ]]\nThe '''Red August''' ({{zh|s=\u7ea2\u516b\u6708 |t=\u7d05\u516b\u6708 |p=H\u00f3ng B\u0101yu\u00e8}}), originally meaning the August of 1966 of the [[Cultural Revolution]], is also used to indicate a series of [[massacre]]s in [[Beijing]] which mainly took place during the period.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/docs/2001_03_05.pdf|title=Student Attacks Against Teachers: The Revolution of 1966|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=2001|website=University of Chicago|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k9NQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=Daxing+Massacre#v=onepage|title=Historical Dictionary of the Chinese Cultural Revolution|last=Jian|first=Guo|last2=Song|first2=Yongyi|last3=Zhou|first3=Yuan|date=2015-07-23|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-4422-5172-4|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|date=2014-12-07|title=A Massacre in Daxing County During the Cultural Revolution|journal=Chinese Law & Government|volume=14|issue=3|pages=70\u201371|language=en|doi=10.2753/CLG0009-4609140370}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/11/the-cultural-revolution-50-years-on-all-you-need-to-know-about-chinas-political-convulsion|title=The Cultural Revolution: all you need to know about China's political convulsion|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2016-05-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/09/13/china-communist-party-grandfather-survived-cultural-revolution-why-does-he-still-love-mao/|title=My Grandfather Survived China's Cultural Revolution. Why Does He Still Love Mao?|last=Dong|first=Yifu|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Jian|first=Guo|url=https://books.google.com/?id=T5-4zOdHKOIC&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA237&dq=Historical+Dictionary+of+the+Chinese+Cultural+Revolution+red+august|title=Historical Dictionary of the Chinese Cultural Revolution|last2=Song|first2=Yongyi|last3=Zhou|first3=Yuan|date=2006-07-17|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6491-7|language=en}}</ref> According to the official statistics in 1980, from August to September in 1966, a total of 1,772 people\u2014including teachers and principals of many schools\u2014were killed in Beijing by [[Red Guards]]; in addition, 33,695 homes were ransacked and 85,196 families were forced to leave the city.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifengweekly.com/detil.php?id=604 |script-title=zh:\u600e\u6837\u53cd\u601d\u201c\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u201d|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u5468\u520a|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2011/09/201109160825.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u201c\u975e\u6b63\u5e38\u6b7b\u4ea1\u201d\u4e86\u591a\u5c11\u4eba\uff1f ---- \u8bfb\u82cf\u626c\u7684\u300a\u6587\u9769\u4e2d\u4e2d\u56fd\u519c\u6751\u7684\u96c6\u4f53\u5c60\u6740\u300b|last=Song|first=Yongyi|date=|publisher=\u535a\u8baf|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2014/01/23/265228870/chinese-red-guards-apologize-reopening-a-dark-chapter|title=Chinese Red Guards Apologize, Reopening A Dark Chapter|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> The killing by the Red Guards also made an impact on several rural districts of Beijing, causing the \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\", for example, during which 325 people were killed from August 27 to September 1 in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1994/07/18/a-nightmare-leaves-scars-questions/05791e4e-e4a4-49b8-b235-c440f51783c0/|title=A NIGHTMARE LEAVES SCARS, QUESTIONS|last=Southerl|first=Daniel|date=1994-07-18|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-12-23|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The oldest killed during the Daxing Massacre was 80 years old, while the youngest was only 38 days old; 22 families were wiped out.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://mjlsh.usc.cuhk.edu.hk/Book.aspx?cid=4&tid=2464 |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u65f6\u671f\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5174\u53bf\u5927\u5c60\u6740\u8c03\u67e5|last=Yu|first=Luowen|date=|publisher=Chinese University of Hong Kong|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Scholars have also pointed out that, according to the official statistics in 1985, the actual death toll during the Red August was over 10,000.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://beijingspring.com/bj2/2010/170/201332200545.htm |script-title=zh:\u8bb0\u4e0b\u8001\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u7684\u8840\u503a|last=Peng|first=Xiaoming|date=|publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u4e4b\u6625|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.boxun.com/hero/201203/beijingzhoumoshihui/18_1.shtml |script-title=zh:\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5927\u7b11\u8c08\u6740\u4eba/\u585e\u9e3f\u79cb /\u5317\u4eac\u5468\u672b\u8bd7\u4f1a|author=|first=|date=|publisher=Boxun|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nOn August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Song Binbin]], a leader of the Red Guards, on [[Tiananmen|Tiananmen of Beijing]], which greatly encouraged the Red Guards who then started their massive killing in the city.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Methods of slaughter during the Red August included beating, whipping, strangling, trampling, boiling, beheading and so on; in particular, the method used to kill most infants and children were knocking them against the ground or slicing them in halves.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/victim_ebook_070505.pdf |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u53d7\u96be\u8005 \u2014\u2014\u5173\u4e8e\u8feb\u5bb3\u3001\u76d1\u7981\u548c\u6740\u622e\u7684\u5bfb\u8bbf\u5b9e\u5f55|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=|publisher=[[University of Chicago]] |language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2013/08/201308012335.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5927\u5174\u6587\u9769\u5c60\u6740\uff1a\u5a74\u513f\u88ab\u5288\u6210\u4e24\u534a|author=|first=|date=|publisher=Boxun|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipkmedia.com/%e9%9b%86%e4%bd%93%e9%81%97%e5%bf%98%e6%96%87%e9%9d%a9%ef%bc%8c%e6%97%a0%e7%96%91%e6%98%af%e4%b8%80%e7%a7%8d%e6%9b%b4%e6%b7%b1%e8%bf%9c%e7%9a%84%e6%b0%91%e6%97%8f%e5%85%ac%e8%80%bb/ |script-title=zh:\u96c6\u4f53\u9057\u5fd8\u6587\u9769\uff0c\u65e0\u7591\u662f\u4e00\u79cd\u66f4\u6df1\u8fdc\u7684\u6c11\u65cf\u516c\u803b|last=|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u5149\u4f20\u5a92|language=zh|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Many people, including the notable writer [[Lao She]], committed suicide after being persecuted.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/rct/pdf/e_outputs/b10/v10p005.pdf|title=Death and the Nobel-On Lao She's \"Suicide\"|last=Brady|first=Paul|date=1974|website=Chinese University of Hong Kong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> During the massacres, Mao Zedong publicly opposed any government intervention to the student movement, and [[Xie Fuzhi]], the Minister of [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], also ordered to protect the Red Guards and not arrest them.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=%E5%8C%97%E4%BA%AC+%E5%A6%82%E6%9E%9C%E4%BD%A0%E6%8A%8A%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA%E7%9A%84%E4%BA%BA%E6%89%A3%E7%95%99%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E6%8D%95%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E4%BD%A0%E4%BB%AC%E5%B0%B1%E8%A6%81%E7%8A%AF%E9%94%99%E8%AF%AF#v=onepage |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":33\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/history/zhiqing/ziliao/detail_2012_09/01/17271511_0.shtml?_from_ralated |script-title=zh:\u6587\u9769\u516c\u5b89\u90e8\u957f\u8c22\u5bcc\u6cbb\u8c08\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u6253\u6b7b\u4eba\uff1a\u6211\u4eec\u7ba1\u4e0d\u7740|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/shendu/nfzm/detail_2014_03/14/34768339_0.shtml |script-title=zh:\u535e\u4ef2\u8018\u4e08\u592b\uff1a\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u6ca1\u53c2\u4e0e\u6253\u4eba \u4f46\u5979\u662f\u4e00\u4f19\u513f\u7684|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/history/zhiqing/ziliao/200912/1214_6858_1473893.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5bf9\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u7ec4\u7ec7\u5931\u53bb\u4fe1\u4efb \u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u51b3\u5b9a\u4e0b\u653e\u77e5\u9752\u59cb\u672b|author=|date=|publisher=\u51e4\u51f0\u7f51|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> However, things had grown out of control by the end of August 1966, forcing the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] (CPC) and Chinese government to take multiple interventions, which gradually brought the massacre to an end.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnd.org/CR/ZK06/cr340.gb.html |script-title=zh:\u300a\u4eb2\u5386\u91cd\u5e86\u5927\u6b66\u6597\u300b\u5e8f|author=\u738b\u5e74\u4e00|date=|publisher=\u534e\u590f\u6587\u6458|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nThe Red August of Beijing is regarded as the origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the Chinese Cultural Revolution, influencing the Red Guards' movement in multiple cities including [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Nanjing]] and [[Xiamen]], where local political leaders, intellectuals, teachers and people of [[Five Black Categories]] were persecuted and killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR43&lpg=PR43&dq=%E7%BA%A2%E8%89%B2%E6%81%90%E6%80%96#v=onepage |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|location=|pages=|language=zh|chapter=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/mandarin/zhuanlan/xinlingzhilyu/wengebeiwanglu/m0816mind-08152013163142.html |script-title=zh:47\u5468\u5e74\u56de\u653e\uff1a\u518d\u5fc6\u6587\u9769\u201c\u516b.\u4e00\u516b\u201d\u548c \u201c\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\u201d|work=Radio Free Asia|language=zh-cn|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinesepen.org/blog/archives/61964 |script-title=zh:\u91d1\u949f\uff1a\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\uff0c\u8840\u8ff9\u672a\u4e7e|author=|date=|publisher=\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u6587\u7b14\u4f1a|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://new.qq.com/rain/a/20130928003840 |script-title=zh:1966\u5e74\u9996\u90fd\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u4e0a\u6d77\u641e\u6b66\u6597:\u6ca1\u6253\u6b7b\u5c31\u662f\u6587\u6597|author=|date=|publisher=[[Tencent]] |accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/bianzhongyun_text2.htm |script-title=zh:\u535e\u4ef2\u8018\u7eaa\u5ff5\u6587\u7ae0\uff08\u7eed\uff09|last=Wang|first=Youqin|date=|publisher=University of Chicago|language=zh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> There has been comparison between the 18 August 1966, which was the key point of the Red August, and the ''[[Kristallnacht]],'' which was the prelude of [[Nazi Germany]]'s [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/zh/%E7%8E%8B%E5%AE%B9%E8%8A%AC%E7%BB%8F%E5%8E%86%E7%9A%84818/a-15326044 |script-title=zh:\u738b\u5bb9\u82ac\u7ecf\u5386\u7684\"8\u00b718\"|last=|author=|first=|date=|publisher=\u5fb7\u56fd\u4e4b\u58f0|language=zh|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mjlsh.org/book.aspx?cid=2&tid=2835&pid=7350 |script-title=zh:\u6c89\u91cd\u7684\u56de\u5fc6\uff0841\uff09\u201c\u6587\u9769\u201d\u98ce\u66b4\u5230\u6765\u7684\u65f6\u5019|author=|date=|publisher=[[Chinese University of Hong Kong]] |accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxun.com/news/gb/z_special/2012/04/201204232254.shtml |script-title=zh:\u7280\u5229\u516c\uff1a\u4e5f\u8bf4\u201c\u8001\u7ea2\u536b\u5175\u201d|author=|date=|publisher=\u535a\u8baf|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnd.org/CR/ZK12/cr696.gb.html |script-title=zh:\u4f2b\u89c6\u738b\u6676\u579a\uff0d\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u5bf9\u7c3f\u5386\u53f2\u7684\u516c\u5802\u2014\u2014\u300a\u5b8b\u5f6c\u5f6c\u8c08\u8bdd\u7eaa\u8981\u300b\u7684\u89e3\u8bfb\u53ca\u5176\u5b83\uff08\u4e0b\uff09|author=\u90ce\u94a7|date=|publisher=\u534e\u590f\u6587\u6458|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite journal|last=Ma|first=Sheng-Mei|title=Contrasting Two Survival Literatures: On the Jewish Holocaust and the Chinese Cultural Revolution|date=1987-01-01|url=https://academic.oup.com/hgs/article/2/1/81/759930|journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=81\u201393|doi=10.1093/hgs/2.1.81|issn=8756-6583}}</ref> The Red August along with the following massacres across China during the Cultural Revolution has also been compared to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] made by the [[Armed Forces of the Empire of Japan|Japanese military]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20181213-notes-nanjing-massacre/ |script-title=zh:\u8b80\u8005\u4f86\u51fd\uff1a\u5efa\u69cb\u6587\u5316\u5275\u50b7\u2014\u2014\u5f9e\u5357\u4eac\u5927\u5c60\u6bba\u8207\u300c\u6587\u9769\u300d\u8aaa\u8d77|author=\u843d\u65e5\u9918\u71c8|date=|publisher=\u7aef\u50b3\u5a92\u79d1\u6280|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://listsprd.osu.edu/pipermail/mclc/2016-May/005028.html|title=MCLC: Ma JIan on the CR anniversary|last=LIST|first=MCLC|date=2016|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== History of the massacre ==\n\n=== Historical background ===\nOn May 16, 1966, Cultural Revolution began in [[Mainland China|mainland, China]]. On August 5th, [[Bian Zhongyun]], the first vice-principal of the [[Experimental High School Attached to Beijing Normal University]], was beaten to death by [[Red Guards]] and was first education worker in Beijing killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Massacre in Beijing ===\nOn August 18, 1966, [[Mao Zedong]] met with [[Song Binbin]], a leader of the Red Guards, on [[Tiananmen|Tiananmen of Beijing]], where Mao asked Song if the \"Bin\" in her first name was the same character as the \"Bin\" in [[Chengyu|Chinese Chengyu]] \"Wen Zhi Bin Bin (\u6587\u8d28\u5f6c\u5f6c)\"; later, Mao commented on her name, \u201cYao Wu Ma (\u8981\u6b66\u561b)\u201d, meaning \"(you'd) better fight\". <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> After this meeting, the morale of the Red Guards was significantly boosted, which triggered their massive slaughter in Beijing.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> In particular, on August 25, 1966, thousands of Red Guards started a week-long massacre in Ganlan Market (\u6984\u6746\u5e02) of the [[Chongwen District]] of Beijing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/317716627_99911659|title=\u6984\u6746\u5e02\u4e8b\u4ef6_\u5317\u4eac|website=www.sohu.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, 1966, Mao approved a document from the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], ordering \"do not use police force\u2014no exception\u2014to intervene or suppress the movement of revolutionary students\".<ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/mandarin/zhuanlan/xinlingzhilyu/wengebeiwanglu/m0816mind-08152013163142.html|title=47\u5468\u5e74\u56de\u653e\uff1a\u518d\u5fc6\u6587\u9769\"\u516b.\u4e00\u516b\"\u548c \"\u7ea2\u516b\u6708\"|website=Radio Free Asia|language=zh-cn|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite book|last=\u718a\u666f\u660e|url=https://books.google.com/?id=diezDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=%E5%8C%97%E4%BA%AC+%E5%A6%82%E6%9E%9C%E4%BD%A0%E6%8A%8A%E6%89%93%E4%BA%BA%E7%9A%84%E4%BA%BA%E6%89%A3%E7%95%99%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E6%8D%95%E8%B5%B7%E6%9D%A5%EF%BC%8C%E4%BD%A0%E4%BB%AC%E5%B0%B1%E8%A6%81%E7%8A%AF%E9%94%99%E8%AF%AF#v=onepage|title=\u4e2d\u5916\u5b78\u8005\u8ac7\u6587\u9769|last2=\u5b8b\u6c38\u6bc5|last3=\u4f59\u570b\u826f|date=2018-06-15|publisher=The Chinese University Press|isbn=978-988-17563-3-6|language=ru}}</ref> The next day, Mao gave a talk at the Work Conference of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Center]], publicly supporting students' movement and opposing any intervention to the Cultural Revolution of students:<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-9/mswv9_65.htm|title=Talk At The Work Conference Of The Centre|website=www.marxists.org|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/chinese/maozedong/1968/5-209.htm|author=|date=|publisher=\u4e2d\u6587\u9a6c\u514b\u601d\u4e3b\u4e49\u6587\u5e93|script-title=zh:\u6bdb\u6cfd\u4e1c\u5728\u4e2d\u592e\u5de5\u4f5c\u4f1a\u8bae\u4e0a\u7684\u8bb2\u8bdd\uff08\u4e00\u4e5d\u516d\u516d\u5e74\u516b\u6708\u4e8c\u5341\u4e09\u65e5\uff09|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref><blockquote>In my view, Peking is not all that chaotic. The students held a meeting of 100,000 and then captured the murderers. This caused some panic. Peking is too gentle. Appeals have been issued, [but after all] there are very few hooligans. Stop interfering for the time being. It is still too early to say anything definite about the reorganization of the centre of the [Youth] League; let us wait four months. Decisions taken hurriedly can do only harm. Work teams were dispatched in a hurry; the left was struggled against in a hurry; meetings of 100,000 were called in a hurry; appeals were issued in a hurry; opposition to the new municipal [party] committee of Peking was said, in a hurry, to be tantamount to an opposition to the [party] Centre. Why is it impermissible to oppose K? I have issued a big character poster myself, \u2018Bombard the Headquarters!\u2019 Some problems have to be settled soon. For instance, the workers, peasants, and soldiers should not interfere with the students\u2019 great Cultural Revolution. Let the students go into the street. What is wrong with their writing big-character posters or going into the street? Let foreigners take pictures. They take shots to show aspects of our backward tendencies. But it does not matter. Let the imperialists make a scandal about us.</blockquote>On August 26, [[Xie Fuzhi]], the Minister of [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]], also ordered to protect the Red Guards and not arrest them; he stated that it was not incorrect for the Red Guards to beat \"bad people\", and it was fine if the \"bad people\" were killed.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> The next day, the \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\" took place in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> Xie reiterated his points while meeting with the heads of several provincial public security systems, claiming that the killing by Red Guards was none of their business and it was a mistake if the public security was to arrest the Red Guards.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":31\" />\n\n=== The end of the massacre ===\nBy the end of August 1966, things had grown out of control, forcing the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] (CPC) and Chinese government to take multiple interventions, which gradually brought the massacre to an end.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> On September 5, ''[[People's Daily]]'' published an article (\"\u7528\u6587\u6597\uff0c\u4e0d\u7528\u6b66\u6597\"), calling for an end to the combat and massacre.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u8457|first=\u6768\u7ee7\u7ef3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT508&lpg=PT508&dq=%E7%94%A8%E6%96%87%E6%96%97%EF%BC%8C%E4%B8%8D%E7%94%A8%E6%AD%A6%E6%96%97+9%E6%9C%885%E6%97%A5#v=onepage|title=\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|language=zh}}</ref> \n\nNevertheless, millions of Red Guards continued to arrive in Beijing to see Mao Zedong at Tiananmen square on September 15 and October 1.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== The slaughter ==\n\n=== Methods of killing ===\nDuring the Red August, methods of slaughter used by Red Guards included beating, whipping, strangling, trampling, boiling, beheading and so on; in particular, the method used to kill most infants and children were knocking them against the ground or slicing them in halves.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\n=== Death toll ===\n\n* According to the official statistics in 1980, from August to September in 1966, a total of 1,772 people\u2014including teachers and principals of many schools\u2014were killed in Beijing by [[Red Guards]]; in addition, 33,695 homes were ransacked and 85,196 families were forced to leave Beijing.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":20\" /> \n* In \"[[Daxing Massacre]]\", 325 people were killed from August 27 to September 1 in [[Daxing District|Daxing District of Beijing]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n* Researchers have pointed out that, according to the official statistics in 1985, the actual death toll during the Red August was over 10,000; in addition, 92,000 homes were ransacked and 125,000 families were forced to leave the city.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":13\" />\n\n== Aftermath and influence ==\n[[File:Political_slogan_by_Red_Guards_on_the_campus_of_Fudan_University_1976.jpg|alt=|thumb|The Red Guards' political propaganda slogans on the wall of the campus of [[Shanghai Fudan University]]: \"Defend the Central Party Committee with blood and life! Defend Chairman Mao with blood and life! \u201d.]]\nThe Red August of Beijing is regarded as the origin of the [[Red Terror]] of the Chinese Cultural Revolution.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Some of the Red Guards from Beijing No.6 High School even wrote \"Long Live Red Terror!\" on the wall with the blood of their victims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/wangguanghua.htm|title=\u5b66\u751f\u738b\u5149\u534e\u4e4b\u6b7b|author=Youqin, Wang|date=|work=The University of Chicago|publisher=|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226161900/http://ywang.uchicago.edu/history/wangguanghua.htm|archive-date=2018-12-26|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> Red August made an impact on the movement of Red Guards in multiple cities including [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], [[Nanjing]] and [[Xiamen]], where local political leaders, intellectuals, teachers and people of [[Five Black Categories]] were persecuted and killed by the Red Guards.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":28\" /><ref name=\":26\" /> For instance, on September 15, 1966, eleven Red Guards from [[Beijing Foreign Studies University]] united with Red Guards from [[Shanghai Foreign Language School]] in Shanghai, chanting \"Long Live Red Terror\" and subsequently persecuting 31 teachers.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nThere has been comparison between the 18 August 1966, which was the key point of the Red August, and the ''[[Kristallnacht]],'' which was the prelude of [[Nazi Germany]]'s [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":30\" /> The Red August along with the following massacres across China during the Cultural Revolution has also been compared to the [[Nanjing Massacre]] made by the [[Armed Forces of the Empire of Japan|Japanese military]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Red Terror]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n*[[Daxing Massacre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Political controversies in China]]\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights in China]]\n[[Category:1966 in Asia]]\n[[Category:1966 in China]]\n[[Category:1960s in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n", "name_user": "SCreditC", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_August"}
